		<p class="comment-meta"> 
			<time class="comment-published" datetime="2008-12-01T21:40:06+00:00" title="Monday, December 1, 2008, 9:40 pm" itemprop="commentTime"><a href="http://www.createdinbirmingham.com/2008/12/01/thoughts-on-the-creative-city-awards-2008/#comment-42056">December 1, 2008 at 9:40 pm</a></time>
					</p>
		<div class="comment-content">
			<p>Yes, I reckon you&#8217;re right on the marketing front. For example, emailing past winners to bump up the number of nominations is unlikely to get fresh faces involved (esp when they win again).</p>
<p>Whether this is a worry. Well, in one sense there are bigger problems in the world that need sorting first. Also, the awards are described as a way of packaging and selling the city&#8217;s creative sector outside the city. If that&#8217;s the case then we&#8217;re well represented by the winners.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s the process behind getting those winners that seems hugely flawed. I mean, who the heck admires a city&#8217;s creative sector by looking at the bank balance and staff turnover first?</p>
		</div><!-- .comment-content -->
